---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import Calculator from '../components/Calculator.jsx';
---
<BaseLayout
  title="EV Charging Cost Calculator | Voltloop"
  description="Free EV charging cost calculator. Estimate the real cost to charge any electric vehicle at home, work, or on a DC fast charger."
>
  <h1>EV Charging Cost Calculator</h1>
  <p class="lede">
    The average U.S. home rate is around <strong>$0.16/kWh</strong>. A typical 60 kWh
    top-up from 20% to 80% works out to roughly <strong>$5–$10</strong> at home, or
    <strong>$15–$25</strong> on a DC fast charger.
  </p>

  <Calculator client:load />

  <h2>Why home charging is almost always cheapest</h2>
  <p>
    Home Level 2 charging at residential rates is consistently cheaper per kWh than DC fast
    charging. Public DC fast chargers — including Tesla Superchargers — typically run
    <strong>$0.30–$0.50/kWh</strong>, two to three times the cost of charging in your garage.
  </p>

  <h2>Inputs that drive the cost</h2>
  <ul class="related">
    <li><strong>Battery size</strong> — bigger battery, more kWh to fill.</li>
    <li><strong>Current vs target %</strong> — most daily charging is a partial top-up, not 0→100%.</li>
    <li><strong>Rate ($/kWh)</strong> — varies by utility, plan, and time of day.</li>
    <li><strong>Charger type</strong> — affects how long the session takes, not the energy delivered.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    See specific vehicle examples like the
    <a href="/tesla-model-3-charging-cost">Tesla Model 3</a> or compare to the
    <a href="/tesla-supercharger-cost">Tesla Supercharger network</a>.
  </p>
</BaseLayout>
